thirteenth century.The twin themes of authority and resistance are the focus of this volume, explored through topics such as landholding and secular politics, the church and religious orders and contemporary imagery and its reception. Together, thepapers combine to illustrate the variety of ways in which historians of the "long" thirteenth century are able to examine the practices and norms through which individuals and institutions sought to establish their authority, andthe ways in which these were open to challenge. JANET BURTON is Professor of Medieval History at University of Wales: Trinity Saint David; PHILLIPP SCHOFIELD is Professor of Medieval History at Aberystwyth University; BJORN WEILER is Professor of History at Aberystwyth University. Contributors: Helen Birkett, Richard Cassidy, Judith Collard, Peter Coss, Ian Forrest, Philippa Hoskin, Jennifer Jahner, Melissa Julian Jones, Fergus Oakes, John Sabapathy, Sita Steckel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGovernment, Resistance tovCongressesxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  amonarchy.  apolitical history.1 aBirkett, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurton, Janet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCassidy, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollard, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoss, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrest, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoskin, Philippa M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoskin, Philippa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJahner, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4ht